{"title_page": "Tommy Boyle (footballer, born 1886)", "text_new": "{{About|the footballer born 1886||Tommy Boyle (disambiguation){{!}}Tommy Boyle}}\n{{short description|English footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Tommy Boyle\n| fullname = Thomas William Boyle<ref name=englandfootballonline>{{cite web|title=Tommy Boyle|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamPlyrsBios/PlayersB/BioBoyleTW.html|publisher=www.englandfootballonline.com|accessdate=23 February 2014}}</ref>\n| image = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1886|1|29|df=y}}<ref name=englandfootballonline/>\n| birth_place = [[Hoyland]], England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1940|1|5|1886|1|29|df=y}}<ref name=\"11v11\" />\n| position = [[Wing half|Half back]]\n| death_place = [[Whittingham, Lancashire|Whittingham]], England<ref>{{Cite book |title=The Road to Glory \u2013 Burnley's FA Cup Triumph in 1914 |last=Smith |first=Mike |date=10 March 2014 |publisher=Grosvenor House Publishing |isbn=9781781482605 |language=en}}</ref>\n| height = \n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = Hoyland Star\n| youthyears2 = \n| youthclubs2 = Elsecar Athletic\n| years1 = 1906\u20131912\n| clubs1 = [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]]\n| caps1 = 160\n| goals1 = 17\n| years2 = 1912\u20131923\n| clubs2 = [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]\n| caps2 = 210\n| goals2 = 36\n| years3 = 1923\u20131924\n| clubs3 = [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]]\n| caps3 = 7\n| goals3 = 0\n| totalcaps = 377\n| totalgoals = 53\n| nationalyears1 = 1912\u20131919\n| nationalteam1 = [[Football League XI]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 4\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 1913\n| nationalteam2 = [[England national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 1\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 1916\n| nationalteam3 = [[England national football team|England]] (wartime)\n| nationalcaps3 = 1\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n}}\n'''Thomas William Boyle''' (29 January 1886 \u2013 5 January 1940) was an English [[association football|footballer]], primarily associated with [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref>{{cite book | title=England: Player by player | publisher=Green Umbrella Publishing|last= Betts|first= Graham | year=2006| isbn=1-905009-63-1|page=43}}</ref>\n\nTommy Boyle is the only player to have captained a Burnley team in a winning [[FA Cup]] Final. He was a [[Yorkshire]]man born in the village of [[Hoyland]] near [[Barnsley]], and he started his career at [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] In 1912 Boyle crossed the [[Pennines]] to sign for Burnley for what was then a club record fee of \u00a31,150.\n\nHe was described as a great header of the ball, an excellent passer with great leadership qualities, and as being one of the best players ever to play for Burnley. Having lifted the [[FA Cup]] in [[FA Cup Final 1914|1914]], he then became the first Burnley captain to lift the [[Football League First Division|League Championship]] Trophy as Burnley won the [[1920-21 in English football|1920\u201321]] title.\n\nBy then, he was 33 and his career was coming to an end. That season was to be his last full season in the first team. He made his last appearance for Burnley during the 1921\u201322 season, and after a further year playing in the reserves he signed for [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]], where he ended his playing career.\n\nAfter his playing career, he had a spell coaching in Germany.<ref name=englandfootballonline/>\n\nHe won only one [[England national football team|England]] cap against [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] in [[Belfast]] in 1913.<ref name=\"11v11\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/tommy-boyle-64828/ |title=Tommy Boyle |website=11v11.com |access-date=25 July 2018}}</ref> He also played in four representative matches for the [[The Football League XI|Football League]].<ref name=\"11v11\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.englandstats.com/playerreport.php?pid=137 England profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boyle, Tommy}}\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:Barnsley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Burnley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Wrexham A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:1886 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Hoyland]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football wing halves]]\n[[Category:English Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Royal Field Artillery soldiers]]\n[[Category:British military personnel of World War I]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the footballer born 1886||Tommy Boyle (disambiguation){{!}}Tommy Boyle}}\n{{short description|English footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Tommy Boyle\n| fullname = Thomas William Boyle<ref name=englandfootballonline>{{cite web|title=Tommy Boyle|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamPlyrsBios/PlayersB/BioBoyleTW.html|publisher=www.englandfootballonline.com|accessdate=23 February 2014}}</ref>\n| image = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1886|1|29|df=y}}<ref name=englandfootballonline/>\n| birth_place = [[Hoyland]], England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1940|1|5|1886|1|29|df=y}}<ref name=\"11v11\" />\n| position = [[Wing half|Half back]]\n| death_place = [[Whittingham, Lancashire|Whittingham]], England<ref>{{Cite book |title=The Road to Glory \u2013 Burnley's FA Cup Triumph in 1914 |last=Smith |first=Mike |date=10 March 2014 |publisher=Grosvenor House Publishing |isbn=9781781482605 |language=en}}</ref>\n| height = \n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = Hoyland Star\n| youthyears2 = \n| youthclubs2 = Elsecar Athletic\n| years1 = 1906\u20131912\n| clubs1 = [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]]\n| caps1 = 160\n| goals1 = 17\n| years2 = 1912\u20131923\n| clubs2 = [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]\n| caps2 = 210\n| goals2 = 36\n| years3 = 1923\u20131924\n| clubs3 = [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]]\n| caps3 = 7\n| goals3 = 0\n| totalcaps = 377\n| totalgoals = 53\n| nationalyears1 = 1912\u20131919\n| nationalteam1 = [[Football League XI]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 4\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 1913\n| nationalteam2 = [[England national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 1\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 1916\n| nationalteam3 = [[England national football team|England]] (wartime)\n| nationalcaps3 = 1\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n}}\n'''Thomas William Boyle''' (29 January 1886 \u2013 5 January 1940) was an English [[association football|footballer]], primarily associated with [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref>{{cite book | title=England: Player by player | publisher=Green Umbrella Publishing|last= Betts|first= Graham | year=2006| isbn=1-905009-63-1|page=43}}</ref>\n\nTommy Boyle is the only player to have captained a Burnley team in a winning [[FA Cup]] Final. He was a [[Yorkshire]]man born in the village of [[Hoyland]] near [[Barnsley]], and he started his career at [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] In 1912 Boyle crossed the [[Pennines]] to sign for Burnley for what was then a club record fee of \u00a31,150.\n\nHe was described as a great header of the ball, an excellent passer with great leadership qualities, and as being one of the best players ever to play for Burnley. Having lifted the [[FA Cup]] in [[FA Cup Final 1914|1914]], he then became the first Burnley captain to lift the [[Football League First Division|League Championship]] Trophy as Burnley won the [[1920-21 in English football|1920\u201321]] title.\n\nBy then, he was 33 and his career was coming to an end. That season was to be his last full season in the first team. He made his last appearance for Burnley during the 1921\u201322 season, and after a further year playing in the reserves he signed for [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]], where he ended his playing career.\n\nAfter his playing career, he had a spell coaching in Germany.<ref name=englandfootballonline/>\n\nHe won only one [[England national football team|England]] cap against [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] in [[Belfast]] in 1913.<ref name=\"11v11\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/tommy-boyle-64828/ |title=Tommy Boyle |website=11v11.com |access-date=25 July 2018}}</ref> He also played in four representative matches for the [[The Football League XI|Football League]].<ref name=\"11v11\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.englandstats.com/playerreport.php?pid=137 England profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boyle, Tommy}}\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:Barnsley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Burnley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Wrexham A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:1886 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Hoyland]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football wing halves]]\n[[Category:English Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Royal Field Artillery soldiers]]\n[[Category:British military personnel of World War I]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Boyle_(footballer,_born_1886)"}
{"title_page": "Tommy Bowman", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Tommy Bowman\n| image = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Thomas Bowman\n| height = \n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1873|10|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Tarbolton]], Scotland\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=y|1958|8|27|1873|10|26}}\n| death_place = [[Southampton]], England\n| position = [[Defender (football)|Half back]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1891\u20131896\n| years2 = 1896\u20131897 \n| years3 = 1897\u20131901 \n| years4 = 1901\u20131904 \n| years5 = 1904\u20131909 \n| years6 = 1909\u20131912 \n| clubs1 = [[Annbank F.C.|Annbank]] \n| clubs2 = [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]\n| clubs3 = [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]\n| clubs4 = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] \n| clubs5 = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] \n| clubs6 = [[Eastleigh Athletic F.C.|Eastleigh Athletic]]\n| caps1 = ?\n| caps2 = 30\n| caps3 = 100\n| caps4 = 88\n| caps5 = 85\n| caps6 = ?\n| goals1 = ?\n| goals2 = 2\n| goals3 = 2\n| goals4 = 2\n| goals5 = 3\n| goals6 = ? \n| managerclubs1 = \n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| club-update = \n| ntupdate =\n}}\n'''Thomas Bowman''' (26 October 1873 in [[Tarbolton]] \u2013 27 August 1958 in [[Southampton]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Tommy Bowman|url=http://www.astonvillaplayerdatabase.com/148.html|work=Aston Villa player database|accessdate=22 August 2010}}</ref>) was a Scottish professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (football)|half back]] in the [[FA Cup Final 1902|1902 FA Cup final]] for [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBowman began his professional career at [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] in 1896, making his debut in the club's first-ever game in [[the Football League]], a 3\u20131 defeat at [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] on 5 September. His [[Blackpool F.C. season 1896-97#Player statistics|thirty league appearances in 1896\u201397]] made him an ever-present in the team.\n\nHe joined [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] [[1897-98 in English football|the following season]] where he gained a reputation as a strong, determined centre-half. He went on to make one hundred league appearances for the club (plus thirteen in the [[FA Cup]]) in four years, helping them to the League titles in [[1898-99 in English football|1898\u201399]] and [[1899-00 in English football|1899-00]]. Bowman was also in the Villa side that lost a 1900 FA cup quarter final against [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall Athletic]] that stunned the football world at the time.<ref>[http://www.freewebs.com/captainbeecher/number18.htm Match report Aston Villa vs Millwall Athletic]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref>\n\nIn 1901, [[Southern Football League|Southern League]] champions Southampton, anxious to replace [[Arthur Chadwick]], who had moved to [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], signed Bowman. In his first season at [[The Dell (Southampton F.C.)|The Dell]], Bowman helped Saints to the [[FA Cup Final 1902|FA Cup final]], whilst finishing only third in the Southern League.\n\nIn 1902\u201303 he was a key member of the team that claimed the Southern League title, a feat repeated the following season when Bowman appeared in all 34 matches. In his three years with the Saints he was a fixture in the half-back line and missed only five league games, making eighty-eight league and thirteen FA Cup appearances, scoring three goals.\n\nAlthough he never received full international honours, he represented the Anglo-Scots against the Scots in 1902.\n\nIn 1904, he joined Chadwick at [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]. In five years at [[Fratton Park]], he made a total of 144 appearances, scoring five goals.\n\nHe finished his career with [[Eastleigh Athletic F.C.|Eastleigh Athletic]] in 1912.\n\nAfter retirement from football, he returned to his original trade as a boiler scaler, where he worked in Southampton Docks for many years.\n\n==Honours==\n'''Aston Villa'''\n* [[The Football League|Football League]] championship: [[1898-99 in English football|1898\u201399]], [[1899-00 in English football|1899\u20131900]]\n\n'''Southampton'''\n* [[FA Cup]] finalist: [[FA Cup Final 1902|1902]]\n* [[Southern Football League|Southern League]] championship: 1902\u201303, 1903\u201304\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{cite book | first=Roy | last=Calley| coauthors= | title=Blackpool: A Complete Record 1887\u20131992 | publisher=Breedon Books Sport | location= | year=1992 | editor= | isbn=1-873626-07-X}}\n*{{cite book |   author=Duncan Holley & Gary Chalk |   title=The Alphabet of the Saints|   publisher= ACL & Polar Publishing |   year=1992|   isbn=0-9514862-3-3}}\n*{{cite book |   author=Gary Chalk & Duncan Holley |   title=Saints \u2013 A complete record|   publisher= Breedon Books|   year=1987|   isbn=0-907969-22-4}}\n*{{cite book |   author=Dave Juson & others |   title=Saints v Pompey \u2013 A history of unrelenting rivalry|   publisher=Hagiology Publishing |   year=2004|   isbn=0-9534474-5-6}}\n*{{cite book |   author=Mike Neasom, Mick Cooper & Doug Robinson  |   title=Pompey: The History of Portsmouth Football Club|   publisher=Milestone Publications |   year=1984|   isbn=0-903852-50-0}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bowman, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1873 births]]\n[[Category:People from Tarbolton]]\n[[Category:1958 deaths]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Blackpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aston Villa F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southampton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Portsmouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southern Football League players]]\n[[Category:Eastleigh Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from South Ayrshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Tommy Bowman\n| image = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Thomas Bowman\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=8}} \n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1873|10|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Tarbolton]], Scotland\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=y|1958|8|27|1873|10|26}}\n| death_place = [[Southampton]], England\n| position = [[Defender (football)|Half back]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1891\u20131896\n| years2 = 1896\u20131897 \n| years3 = 1897\u20131901 \n| years4 = 1901\u20131904 \n| years5 = 1904\u20131909 \n| years6 = 1909\u20131912 \n| clubs1 = [[Annbank F.C.|Annbank]] \n| clubs2 = [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]\n| clubs3 = [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]\n| clubs4 = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] \n| clubs5 = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] \n| clubs6 = [[Eastleigh Athletic F.C.|Eastleigh Athletic]]\n| caps1 = ?\n| caps2 = 30\n| caps3 = 100\n| caps4 = 88\n| caps5 = 85\n| caps6 = ?\n| goals1 = ?\n| goals2 = 2\n| goals3 = 2\n| goals4 = 2\n| goals5 = 3\n| goals6 = ? \n| managerclubs1 = \n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| club-update = \n| ntupdate =\n}}\n'''Thomas Bowman''' (26 October 1873 in [[Tarbolton]] \u2013 27 August 1958 in [[Southampton]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Tommy Bowman|url=http://www.astonvillaplayerdatabase.com/148.html|work=Aston Villa player database|accessdate=22 August 2010}}</ref>) was a Scottish professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (football)|half back]] in the [[FA Cup Final 1902|1902 FA Cup final]] for [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBowman began his professional career at [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] in 1896, making his debut in the club's first-ever game in [[the Football League]], a 3\u20131 defeat at [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] on 5 September. His [[Blackpool F.C. season 1896-97#Player statistics|thirty league appearances in 1896\u201397]] made him an ever-present in the team.\n\nHe joined [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] [[1897-98 in English football|the following season]] where he gained a reputation as a strong, determined centre-half. He went on to make one hundred league appearances for the club (plus thirteen in the [[FA Cup]]) in four years, helping them to the League titles in [[1898-99 in English football|1898\u201399]] and [[1899-00 in English football|1899-00]]. Bowman was also in the Villa side that lost a 1900 FA cup quarter final against [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall Athletic]] that stunned the football world at the time.<ref>[http://www.freewebs.com/captainbeecher/number18.htm Match report Aston Villa vs Millwall Athletic]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref>\n\nIn 1901, [[Southern Football League|Southern League]] champions Southampton, anxious to replace [[Arthur Chadwick]], who had moved to [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], signed Bowman. In his first season at [[The Dell (Southampton F.C.)|The Dell]], Bowman helped Saints to the [[FA Cup Final 1902|FA Cup final]], whilst finishing only third in the Southern League.\n\nIn 1902\u201303 he was a key member of the team that claimed the Southern League title, a feat repeated the following season when Bowman appeared in all 34 matches. In his three years with the Saints he was a fixture in the half-back line and missed only five league games, making eighty-eight league and thirteen FA Cup appearances, scoring three goals.\n\nAlthough he never received full international honours, he represented the Anglo-Scots against the Scots in 1902.\n\nIn 1904, he joined Chadwick at [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]. In five years at [[Fratton Park]], he made a total of 144 appearances, scoring five goals.\n\nHe finished his career with [[Eastleigh Athletic F.C.|Eastleigh Athletic]] in 1912.\n\nAfter retirement from football, he returned to his original trade as a boiler scaler, where he worked in Southampton Docks for many years.\n\n==Honours==\n'''Aston Villa'''\n* [[The Football League|Football League]] championship: [[1898-99 in English football|1898\u201399]], [[1899-00 in English football|1899\u20131900]]\n\n'''Southampton'''\n* [[FA Cup]] finalist: [[FA Cup Final 1902|1902]]\n* [[Southern Football League|Southern League]] championship: 1902\u201303, 1903\u201304\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{cite book | first=Roy | last=Calley| coauthors= | title=Blackpool: A Complete Record 1887\u20131992 | publisher=Breedon Books Sport | location= | year=1992 | editor= | isbn=1-873626-07-X}}\n*{{cite book |   author=Duncan Holley & Gary Chalk |   title=The Alphabet of the Saints|   publisher= ACL & Polar Publishing |   year=1992|   isbn=0-9514862-3-3}}\n*{{cite book |   author=Gary Chalk & Duncan Holley |   title=Saints \u2013 A complete record|   publisher= Breedon Books|   year=1987|   isbn=0-907969-22-4}}\n*{{cite book |   author=Dave Juson & others |   title=Saints v Pompey \u2013 A history of unrelenting rivalry|   publisher=Hagiology Publishing |   year=2004|   isbn=0-9534474-5-6}}\n*{{cite book |   author=Mike Neasom, Mick Cooper & Doug Robinson  |   title=Pompey: The History of Portsmouth Football Club|   publisher=Milestone Publications |   year=1984|   isbn=0-903852-50-0}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bowman, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1873 births]]\n[[Category:People from Tarbolton]]\n[[Category:1958 deaths]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]] \n[[Category:Blackpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aston Villa F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southampton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Portsmouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southern Football League players]]\n[[Category:Eastleigh Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from South Ayrshire]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, remove unref height", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Bowman"}
{"title_page": "Tommy Booth", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name               = Tommy Booth\n| image               =\n| caption             = \n| fullname            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1949|11|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Middleton, Greater Manchester|Middleton]], England\n| height              = \n| position            = [[Defender (association football)|Central defender]]\n| youthyears1         = 1965\u20131967\n| youthclubs1         = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]\n| years1  = 1967\u20131981 | clubs1  = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]     | caps1  = 382 | goals1  = 25\n| years2  = 1981\u20131984 | clubs2  = [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] | caps2  = 84  | goals2  = 2\n| nationalyears1      = 1969\u20131976\n| nationalteam1       = [[England national under-23 football team|England U23]] | nationalcaps1  = 4 | nationalgoals1  = 0\n| manageryears1       = 1985\u20131986 | managerclubs1  = [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]]\n}}\n'''Tommy Booth''' (born 9 November 1949) is an English former [[association football|footballer]] who played in [[the Football League]] for [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]],<ref name=NB>{{cite web |url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player3/tommybooth.html |title=Tommy Booth |work=UK A\u2013Z Transfers |publisher=Neil Brown |accessdate=6 December 2009}}</ref> and was [[cap (sport)|capped]] four times for [[England national under-23 football team|England at under-23]] level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng-u23-intres-det.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040413100658/http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng-u23-intres-det.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=13 April 2004 |title=England - U-23 International Results- Details |publisher=RSSSF |date=27 March 2004 |first=Barrie |last=Courtney |accessdate=6 December 2009 }}</ref>\n\nBooth was born in [[Middleton, Greater Manchester|Middleton]], [[Lancashire]].<ref name=NB/> He began his career with [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], signing amateur forms in 1965, turning professional in 1967, and making his [[Football League]] debut on 9 October 1968 in a 1\u20131 draw at home to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/displayhero_club.asp?HeroID=36463 |title=Tommy Booth Manchester City FC part 1 |first=Ian |last=Penney |work=Football Heroes |publisher=Sporting Heroes Collections |accessdate=6 December 2009}}</ref> He played in the [[Defender (association football)|centre of defence]], winning [[FA Cup]], [[European Cup Winners' Cup]] and two [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] winners' medals. He played 382 times for City in the League between 1968 and 1981, scoring 25 goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/displayhero_club.asp?HeroID=36464 |title=Tommy Booth Manchester City FC part 2 |first=Ian |last=Penney |work=Football Heroes |publisher=Sporting Heroes Collections |accessdate=6 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/displayhero_club.asp?HeroID=36466 |title=Tommy Booth Manchester City FC part 4 |first=Ian |last=Penney |work=Football Heroes |publisher=Sporting Heroes Collections |accessdate=6 December 2009}}</ref> In September 1981 he moved to [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] for \u00a330,000. At [[Deepdale]] he made 84 appearances between 1981 and 1984, scoring twice, before injury forced him to retire during the 1984\u201385 season. In February 1985 he was appointed as Preston manager; with the club in difficult financial circumstances, he resigned in January 1986.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/lancashire-evening-post-preston-england/mi_7868/is_2004_March_8/interview-tommy-booth/ai_n33914669/ |title=The Big Interview - Tommy Booth |newspaper=Lancashire Evening Post |format=reprint |publisher=FindArticles |date=8 March 2004 |accessdate=6 December 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Manchester City'''\n* [[Football League First Division]] winner 1967-68\n* [[FA Cup]] winner: [[1969 FA Cup Final|1969]]\n* [[European Cup Winners Cup]] winner: [[1970 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|1970]]\n* [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] winner: [[1970 Football League Cup Final|1970]], [[1976 Football League Cup Final|1976]]\n* [[FA Charity Shield]]: [[1972 FA Charity Shield|1972]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/CommunityShield/1972-73CharityShield.htm |title=1972/73 Charity Shield |website=footballsite.co.uk |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{NeilBrownPlayers|player3/tommybooth}}\n* [http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/searchresults.asp?ButtonLeap=0&countryLinkDescription=+matching+search+results&FootballHeroName=Tommy+Booth&FootballHeroClubCountry=&FootballHeroDecade=Select+One&SearchButton=Search Stats, photos and bio] at Sporting Heroes\n\n{{Preston North End F.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Booth, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Middleton, Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England under-23 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Preston North End F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n[[Category:Preston North End F.C. managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name               = Tommy Booth\n| image               =\n| caption             = \n| fullname            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1949|11|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Middleton, Greater Manchester|Middleton]], England\n| height              = \n| position            = [[Defender (association football)|Central defender]]\n| youthyears1         = 1965\u20131967\n| youthclubs1         = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]\n| years1  = 1967\u20131981 | clubs1  = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]     | caps1  = 382 | goals1  = 25\n| years2  = 1981\u20131984 | clubs2  = [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] | caps2  = 84  | goals2  = 2\n| nationalyears1      = 1969\u20131976\n| nationalteam1       = [[England national under-23 football team|England U23]] | nationalcaps1  = 4 | nationalgoals1  = 0\n| manageryears1       = 1985\u20131986 | managerclubs1  = [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]]\n}}\n'''Tommy Booth''' (born 9 November 1949) is an English former [[association football|footballer]] who played in [[the Football League]] for [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]],<ref name=NB>{{cite web |url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player3/tommybooth.html |title=Tommy Booth |work=UK A\u2013Z Transfers |publisher=Neil Brown |accessdate=6 December 2009}}</ref> and was [[cap (sport)|capped]] four times for [[England national under-23 football team|England at under-23]] level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng-u23-intres-det.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040413100658/http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng-u23-intres-det.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=13 April 2004 |title=England - U-23 International Results- Details |publisher=RSSSF |date=27 March 2004 |first=Barrie |last=Courtney |accessdate=6 December 2009 }}</ref>\n\nBooth was born in [[Middleton, Greater Manchester|Middleton]], [[Lancashire]].<ref name=NB/> He began his career with [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], signing amateur forms in 1965, turning professional in 1967, and making his [[Football League]] debut on 9 October 1968 in a 1\u20131 draw at home to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/displayhero_club.asp?HeroID=36463 |title=Tommy Booth Manchester City FC part 1 |first=Ian |last=Penney |work=Football Heroes |publisher=Sporting Heroes Collections |accessdate=6 December 2009}}</ref> He played in the [[Defender (association football)|centre of defence]], winning [[FA Cup]], [[European Cup Winners' Cup]] and two [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] winners' medals. He played 382 times for City in the League between 1968 and 1981, scoring 25 goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/displayhero_club.asp?HeroID=36464 |title=Tommy Booth Manchester City FC part 2 |first=Ian |last=Penney |work=Football Heroes |publisher=Sporting Heroes Collections |accessdate=6 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/displayhero_club.asp?HeroID=36466 |title=Tommy Booth Manchester City FC part 4 |first=Ian |last=Penney |work=Football Heroes |publisher=Sporting Heroes Collections |accessdate=6 December 2009}}</ref>  In September 1981 he moved to [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] for \u00a330,000. At [[Deepdale]] he made 84 appearances between 1981 and 1984, scoring twice, before injury forced him to retire during the 1984\u201385 season. In February 1985 he was appointed as Preston manager; with the club in difficult financial circumstances, he resigned in January 1986.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/lancashire-evening-post-preston-england/mi_7868/is_2004_March_8/interview-tommy-booth/ai_n33914669/ |title=The Big Interview - Tommy Booth |newspaper=Lancashire Evening Post |format=reprint |publisher=FindArticles |date=8 March 2004 |accessdate=6 December 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Manchester City'''\n* [[Football League First Division]] winner 1967-68\n* [[FA Cup]] winner: [[1969 FA Cup Final|1969]]\n* [[European Cup Winners Cup]] winner: [[1970 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|1970]]\n* [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] winner: [[1970 Football League Cup Final|1970]], [[1976 Football League Cup Final|1976]]\n* [[FA Charity Shield]]: [[1972 FA Charity Shield|1972]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/CommunityShield/1972-73CharityShield.htm |title=1972/73 Charity Shield |website=footballsite.co.uk |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{NeilBrownPlayers|player3/tommybooth}}\n* [http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/searchresults.asp?ButtonLeap=0&countryLinkDescription=+matching+search+results&FootballHeroName=Tommy+Booth&FootballHeroClubCountry=&FootballHeroDecade=Select+One&SearchButton=Search Stats, photos and bio] at Sporting Heroes\n\n{{Preston North End F.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Booth, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Middleton, Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England under-23 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Preston North End F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n[[Category:Preston North End F.C. managers]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Booth"}
{"title_page": "Magikarp", "text_new": "{{Infobox character\n| color       = #149eff\n| name        = Magikarp\n| image       = Pok\u00e9mon Magikarp art.png\n| caption     = '''[[List of Pok\u00e9mon|National Pok\u00e9dex]]'''<br />[[Tauros (Pok\u00e9mon)#Tauros|Tauros]] - '''Magikarp (#129)''' - [[Gyarados]]\n| series      = [[Pok\u00e9mon (video game series)|''Pok\u00e9mon'' series]]\n| firstgame   = [[Pok\u00e9mon Red and Blue|''Pok\u00e9mon Red'' and ''Blue'']]\n| designer      = [[Ken Sugimori]]\n}}\n<!--Please keep this page clear of all bias-->\n'''Magikarp''', known in [[Japan]] as {{nihongo|'''Koiking'''|\u30b3\u30a4\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0|Koikingu}}, is a [[List of Pok\u00e9mon|Pok\u00e9mon species]] in [[Nintendo]] and [[Game Freak]]'s ''[[Pok\u00e9mon]]'' franchise. Created by [[Ken Sugimori]], Magikarp first appeared in the video games [[Pok\u00e9mon Red and Blue|''Pok\u00e9mon Red'' and ''Blue'']] and subsequent sequels. They have later appeared in various merchandise, spinoff titles and animated and printed adaptations of the franchise. Known as the [[Fish]] [[Pok\u00e9mon]], Magikarp is found in many bodies of water, especially lakes, rivers, and ponds. Magikarp is especially well known from the popular mobile game [[Pok\u00e9mon Go]], where it\u2019s featured as a starter Pok\u00e9mon.\n\n==Description==\n\nMagikarp is a red, medium-sized fish. Its notable characteristics include large, heavy scales. Its fins are primarily white, but it has a stiff, three-pointed fin on its back and, a four-pointed fin on its stomach which are both yellow. The shape of the dorsal fin resembles a crown, leading to its Japanese name ''Koiking''. It also has long [[barbels]], which are white on females and tan on males. Although this Pok\u00e9mon is capable of surviving in even the most polluted ponds,<ref name=\"MagikarpSapphire\">{{Pok\u00e9dex|sapphire|Magikarp is virtually useless in battle as it can only splash around. As a result, it is considered to be weak. However, it is actually a very hardy Pok\u00e9mon that can survive in any body of water no matter how polluted it is.}}</ref> it is usually overlooked by trainers because it is pathetically weak.<ref name=\"MagikarpDiamond\">{{Pok\u00e9dex|diamond|It is said to be the world's weakest Pok\u00e9mon. No one knows why it has managed to survive.}}</ref> Even in the heat of battle it will do nothing but flop around. They are normally seen using Splash, which is unusual, as it makes them easy targets to [[predator]]s.<ref name=\"MagikarpSilver\">{{Pok\u00e9dex|silver|For no reason, it jumps and splashes about, making it easy for predators like Pidgeotto to catch it mid-jump.}}</ref> Before the species multiplied, it is believed that the ancestors of Magikarp were actually much stronger than the Magikarp seen today,<ref name=\"MagikarpRed\">{{Pok\u00e9dex|red|In the distant past, it was somewhat stronger than the horribly weak [[Lineal descendant|descendant]]s that exist today.}}</ref> and this belief has led scientists to research this species.<ref name=\"MagikarpRuby\">{{Pok\u00e9dex|ruby|Magikarp is a pathetic excuse for a Pok\u00e9mon that is only capable of flopping and splashing. This behavior prompted scientists to undertake research into it.}}</ref> Long-lived Magikarp are able to utilize their immense splashing power to leap high enough to jump mountains.<ref name=\"MagikarpPlatinum\">{{Pok\u00e9dex|Platinum|A Magikarp living for many years can leap a mountain using Splash. The move remains useless, though.}}</ref> Magikarp is found in many bodies of water, such as lakes, rivers, and ponds.<ref name=\"MagikarpYellow\">{{Pok\u00e9dex|yellow|Famous for being very unreliable. It can be found swimming in seas, lakes, rivers and shallow puddles.}}</ref> It is not a strong swimmer, and currents in the water will sweep it downstream.<ref name=\"MagikarpCrystal\">{{Pok\u00e9dex|crystal|This Pok\u00e9mon gets easily pushed along rivers when there are strong currents. It is very hard to evolve.}}</ref>\n\nThe concept of Magikarp evolving into Gyarados is loosely based on the Chinese mythological tale of the [[Asian carp#In Chinese culture|Carps leaping over the Dragon Gate]]. According to the legend, carps that leap over a legendary waterfall, referred to as the Dragon Gate, are transformed into dragons.\n\nMagikarp has drawn comparisons to [[Feebas]]; however, the latter is usually regarded higher in the gaming community because it can learn far more moves than Magikarp in the Pok\u00e9mon games.\n\n==Appearances==\n\n===In video games===\nIn the video game series, Magikarp is seen commonly when fishing with an Old or Good Rod. In [[Pok\u00e9mon Red and Blue|''Pok\u00e9mon Red'' and ''Blue'']], and [[Pok\u00e9mon FireRed and LeafGreen|their remakes]], an [[Non-player character|NPC]] will sell the player a Magikarp. A similar character appears in [[Pok\u00e9mon Black and White|''Pok\u00e9mon Black'' and ''White'']]. In [[Pok\u00e9mon Diamond and Pearl|''Pok\u00e9mon Diamond'' and ''Pearl'']], Magikarp appear flopping around in a dried up lake. Outside of the main series, in ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Stadium]]'', Magikarp featured in its own mini game called \"Magikarp Splash\", in which players must Splash high enough to hit the button at the top of the screen as many times as it can. A mobile video game, called ''Pok\u00e9mon: Magikarp Jump'', was announced in February 2017 under the title ''Splash! Magikarp'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Funnell|first1=Rob|title='Splash! Magikarp', a Bizarre New Pokemon Title, Has Been Announced for the App Store|url=http://toucharcade.com/2017/02/16/splash-magikarp-announced/|website=TouchArcade|accessdate=19 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218152008/http://toucharcade.com/2017/02/16/splash-magikarp-announced/|archivedate=18 February 2017}}</ref> and was released for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]] on 25 May 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/a-new-pokemon-game-is-out-now-for-mobile/1100-6450325/|title=A New Pokemon Game Is Out Now For Mobile|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006205545/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/a-new-pokemon-game-is-out-now-for-mobile/1100-6450325/|archivedate=2017-10-06}}</ref>\n\n===In other media===\nIn the anime, Magikarp has appeared several times, most notably as the subject of a running gag in which a salesman attempts to trick [[Team Rocket (anime)|Team Rocket]] into buying Magikarp in various guises, the first one being in ''Battle Aboard the St. Anne''.<ref name=\"Battle Aboard the St. Anne\">{{cite episode| title = Battle Aboard the St. Anne | series = [[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]] | credits = Yukiyoshi \u014chashi (writer) | network = Various | airdate = September 28, 1998 | season = [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Indigo League episodes|Indigo League]]|number = 15}}</ref> In ''The Joy of Pok\u00e9mon'', a [[List of Pok\u00e9mon anime characters#Nurse Joy|Nurse Joy]] from the Orange Islands befriended a giant Magikarp that saved her as a child. It evolved into an equally large Gyarados, but it remained friendly.<ref name=\"The Joy of Pok\u00e9mon\">{{cite episode| title = The Joy of Pok\u00e9mon | series = [[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]] | credits = Junki Takegami (writer) | network = Various | airdate = March 4, 2000 | season = [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Adventures on the Orange Islands episodes|Adventures on the Orange Islands]]|number = 92}}</ref> In ''The Wacky Watcher'', [[Ash Ketchum|Ash]], [[Misty (Pok\u00e9mon)|Misty]] and [[Tracey (Pok\u00e9mon)|Tracey]] help a Pok\u00e9mon Watcher named Dr. Quackenpoker observe the migration and evolution of a school of Magikarp.<ref name=\"The Wacky Watcher!\">{{cite episode| title = The Wacky Watcher! | series = [[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]] | credits = Shinz\u014d Fujita (writer) | network = Various | airdate = September 16, 2000 | season = [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Adventures on the Orange Islands episodes|Adventures on the Orange Islands]]|number = 109}}</ref> Another, in ''Ya See We Want an Evolution'', was nicknamed the strongest Magikarp. This Magikarp was unique in that it was in fact able to battle very well, even knocking out Pikachu.<ref name=\"Ya See We Want an Evolution!\">{{cite episode| title = Ya See We Want an Evolution! | series = [[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]] | credits = Yukiyoshi \u014chashi (writer) | network = Various | airdate = July 10, 2007 | season = [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Diamond and Pearl episodes|Diamond and Pearl]]|number = 21}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:Pokemon Magikarp Taiyaki Pancake from Kurikoan, Akihabara shop, Sotokanda 1-15-1 (\u30b3\u30a4\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\u713c\u304d, \u79cb\u8449\u539f \u304f\u308a\u3053\u5eb5, \u5916\u795e\u75301-15-1) (2017-04-06 13.23.04 by Tokyo Girl).jpg|thumb|A Magikarp shaped [[taiyaki]] served in a restaurant in Japan.]] \n[[GamesRadar]] described it as \"[t]he ultimate in useless Pok\u00e9mon\", though noted its evolution [[Gyarados]] as one of the \"biggest\" characters in the series.<ref name=\"Elston, Brett 9\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/the-complete-pokemon-rby-pokedex-part-12/?page=9 |title=The complete Pokemon RBY Pokedex, part 12 |author=Elston, Brett |page=9 |accessdate=2009-10-03 |publisher=[[Future Publishing]] |work=[[GamesRadar]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306111841/http://www.gamesradar.com/the-complete-pokemon-rby-pokedex-part-12/?page=9 |archivedate=2014-03-06 }}</ref> [[IGN]] called it \"possibly the most docile, unassuming, and weak of all the monsters in the Pok\u00e9mon world\"<ref name=\"Gyarados Biography\">{{cite web |url=http://stars.ign.com/objects/143/14349942_biography.html |title=Gyarados Biography |publisher=[[IGN Entertainment]] |work=[[IGN]] |accessdate=2009-10-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Gt7PCd4D?url=http://stars.ign.com/objects/143/14349942_biography.html |archivedate=2013-05-25 }}</ref> and further described it as serving \"solely as [[comic relief]]\", until its evolution into Gyarados.<ref>{{cite web |author=pokemonofthedaychick |publisher=[[IGN]] |title=Pokemon Crystal Version Pok\u00bfmon of the Day: Magikarp (#129) - IGN FAQs |url=http://faqs.ign.com/articles/374/374951p1.html |date=October 21, 2002 |accessdate=2009-10-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205003104/http://faqs.ign.com/articles/374/374951p1.html |archivedate=February 5, 2009 }}</ref> IGN criticized Magikarp as the \"worst Pok\u00e9mon ever\", citing its low statistics and inability to learn moves from Technical or Hidden Machines, calling it a \"Water wussymon.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guides.ign.com/guides/11154/magikarp.html|title=Video Games, Wikis, Cheats, Walkthroughs, Reviews, News & Videos - IGN|website=IGN|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101023213712/http://guides.ign.com/guides/11154/magikarp.html|archivedate=2010-10-23}}</ref> An IGN guide jokingly noted a trainer in ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Platinum]]'' as having the \"best team among those in the area\" due to having six Magikarps, five of which are unable to attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.guides.ign.com/guides/14254510/page_17.html|title=Pokemon Platinum Guide & Walkthrough - Nintendo DS - IGN|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721092100/http://uk.guides.ign.com/guides/14254510/page_17.html|archivedate=2011-07-21}}</ref> The book ''Gaming Cultures and Place in Asia-Pacific'' cited it as an \"example of a common recurring and weak element\" in the games, whose presence rather than function was to \"emphasize the exclusivity and strength of other, rarer creatures for players to find\".<ref name=\"Surman\">{{cite book |title=Gaming Cultures and Place in Asia-Pacific |last=Hjorth |first=Larissa |author2=David Surman |year=2009 |publisher=Taylor and Francis |isbn=978-0-415-99627-3 |chapter=9 |chapter-url=https://newport.academia.edu/documents/0009/2577/MERGEDPOKEMON.pdf |accessdate=2009-06-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620001743/http://newport.academia.edu/documents/0009/2577/MERGEDPOKEMON.pdf |archivedate=2010-06-20 }}</ref> Loredana Lipperini, author of the book ''Generazione Pok\u00e9mon: i bambini e l'invasione planetaria dei nuovi'', described it as \"innocuous-looking.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MOQc163-XCcC|title=Generazione Pok\u00e9mon: i bambini e l'invasione planetaria dei nuovi \"giocattoli di ruolo\"|first=Loredana|last=Lipperini|date=26 May 2017|publisher=Castelvecchi|via=Google Books|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629011754/http://books.google.com/books?id=MOQc163-XCcC|archivedate=29 June 2011|isbn=9788882102494}}</ref> [[Kotaku]]'s Stephen Totilo also gave criticism to Magikarp, commenting that the using it as his character in ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Rumble]]'' made him learn the \"hard way\" that he \"couldn't have had a worse idea.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5353280/at-last-an-easy-pokemon-game|title=At Last, An Easy Pokemon Game|first=Stephen|last=Totilo|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106201728/http://kotaku.com/5353280/at-last-an-easy-pokemon-game|archivedate=2010-01-06}}</ref> The [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]'s Good Game praised ''[[Pok\u00e9Park Wii: Pikachu's Adventure]]'' for its faithfulness to various Pok\u00e9mon's abilities; while Torterra and Hitmontop were described as using Razor Leaf and Rapid Spin, they merely described Magikarp's actions as just \"being Magikarp.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/abc3/goodgamesp/transcripts/s3033267.htm|title=Good Game Spawn Point - PokePark Wii: Pikachu's Adventure|website=www.abc.net.au|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110922154621/http://www.abc.net.au/abc3/goodgamesp/transcripts/s3033267.htm|archivedate=2011-09-22}}</ref> The web site Bright Side of the Sun used an analogy involving Magikarp, commenting that the words \"defense\" and \"rebounding\" were \"tossed around\" more by their coach to them than \"a Magikarp card at a Pok\u00e9mon convention in 1997.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brightsideofthesun.com/2010/12/5/1856751/phoenix-suns-look-to-continue-defensive-magic-on-john-wall-washington|title=Phoenix Suns Look To Continue Defensive Magic Against John Wall, Washington Wizards|date=5 December 2010|website=Bright Side Of The Sun|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101208062651/http://www.brightsideofthesun.com/2010/12/5/1856751/phoenix-suns-look-to-continue-defensive-magic-on-john-wall-washington|archivedate=8 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal|title=Magikarp: The most useless-seeming monster in the Pokeverse hides an awesome secret|journal=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]|issue=249|date=Jan 2013|pages=122\u2013123}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Video games}}\n* [http://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/Magikarp_(Pok\u00e9mon) Magikarp on Bulbapedia]\n* [https://www.pokeapi.co/api/v2/pokemon/magikarp Magikarp on Pokemon.com]\n\n{{Pok\u00e9mon directory}}\n\n[[Category:Fictional fish]]\n[[Category:Pok\u00e9mon species]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 1996]]\n[[Category:Video game characters with water abilities]]\n\n[[ca:L\u00ednia evolutiva de Magikarp#Magikarp]]\n[[es:Anexo:Pok\u00e9mon de la primera generaci\u00f3n#Magikarp]]\n[[pl:Lista Pok\u00e9mon\u00f3w (121-140)#Magikarp]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox character\n| color       = #149eff\n| name        = Magikarp\n| image       = Pok\u00e9mon Magikarp art.png\n| caption     = '''[[List of Pok\u00e9mon|National Pok\u00e9dex]]'''<br />[[Tauros (Pok\u00e9mon)#Tauros|Tauros]] - '''Magikarp (#129)''' - [[Gyarados]]\n| series      = [[Pok\u00e9mon (video game series)|''Pok\u00e9mon'' series]]\n| firstgame   = [[Pok\u00e9mon Red and Blue|''Pok\u00e9mon Red'' and ''Blue'']]\n| designer      = [[Ken Sugimori]]\n}}\n<!--Please keep this page clear of all bias-->\n'''Magikarp''', known in Japan as {{nihongo|'''Koiking'''|\u30b3\u30a4\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0|Koikingu}}, is a [[List of Pok\u00e9mon|Pok\u00e9mon species]] in [[Nintendo]] and [[Game Freak]]'s ''[[Pok\u00e9mon]]'' franchise. Created by [[Ken Sugimori]], Magikarp first appeared in the video games [[Pok\u00e9mon Red and Blue|''Pok\u00e9mon Red'' and ''Blue'']] and subsequent sequels. They have later appeared in various merchandise, spinoff titles and animated and printed adaptations of the franchise. Known as the [[Fish]] [[Pok\u00e9mon]], Magikarp is found in many bodies of water, especially lakes, rivers, and ponds. Magikarp is especially well known from the popular mobile game [[Pok\u00e9mon Go]], where it\u2019s featured as a starter Pok\u00e9mon.\n\n==Description==\n\nMagikarp is a red, medium-sized fish. Its notable characteristics include large, heavy scales. Its fins are primarily white, but it has a stiff, three-pointed fin on its back and, a four-pointed fin on its stomach which are both yellow. The shape of the dorsal fin resembles a crown, leading to its Japanese name ''Koiking''. It also has long [[barbels]], which are white on females and tan on males. Although this Pok\u00e9mon is capable of surviving in even the most polluted ponds,<ref name=\"MagikarpSapphire\">{{Pok\u00e9dex|sapphire|Magikarp is virtually useless in battle as it can only splash around. As a result, it is considered to be weak. However, it is actually a very hardy Pok\u00e9mon that can survive in any body of water no matter how polluted it is.}}</ref> it is usually overlooked by trainers because it is pathetically weak.<ref name=\"MagikarpDiamond\">{{Pok\u00e9dex|diamond|It is said to be the world's weakest Pok\u00e9mon. No one knows why it has managed to survive.}}</ref> Even in the heat of battle it will do nothing but flop around. They are normally seen using Splash, which is unusual, as it makes them easy targets to [[predator]]s.<ref name=\"MagikarpSilver\">{{Pok\u00e9dex|silver|For no reason, it jumps and splashes about, making it easy for predators like Pidgeotto to catch it mid-jump.}}</ref> Before the species multiplied, it is believed that the ancestors of Magikarp were actually much stronger than the Magikarp seen today,<ref name=\"MagikarpRed\">{{Pok\u00e9dex|red|In the distant past, it was somewhat stronger than the horribly weak [[Lineal descendant|descendant]]s that exist today.}}</ref> and this belief has led scientists to research this species.<ref name=\"MagikarpRuby\">{{Pok\u00e9dex|ruby|Magikarp is a pathetic excuse for a Pok\u00e9mon that is only capable of flopping and splashing. This behavior prompted scientists to undertake research into it.}}</ref> Long-lived Magikarp are able to utilize their immense splashing power to leap high enough to jump mountains.<ref name=\"MagikarpPlatinum\">{{Pok\u00e9dex|Platinum|A Magikarp living for many years can leap a mountain using Splash. The move remains useless, though.}}</ref> Magikarp is found in many bodies of water, such as lakes, rivers, and ponds.<ref name=\"MagikarpYellow\">{{Pok\u00e9dex|yellow|Famous for being very unreliable. It can be found swimming in seas, lakes, rivers and shallow puddles.}}</ref> It is not a strong swimmer, and currents in the water will sweep it downstream.<ref name=\"MagikarpCrystal\">{{Pok\u00e9dex|crystal|This Pok\u00e9mon gets easily pushed along rivers when there are strong currents. It is very hard to evolve.}}</ref>\n\nThe concept of Magikarp evolving into Gyarados is loosely based on the Chinese mythological tale of the [[Asian carp#In Chinese culture|Carps leaping over the Dragon Gate]]. According to the legend, carps that leap over a legendary waterfall, referred to as the Dragon Gate, are transformed into dragons.\n\nMagikarp has drawn comparisons to [[Feebas]]; however, the latter is usually regarded higher in the gaming community because it can learn far more moves than Magikarp in the Pok\u00e9mon games.\n\n==Appearances==\n\n===In video games===\nIn the video game series, Magikarp is seen commonly when fishing with an Old or Good Rod. In [[Pok\u00e9mon Red and Blue|''Pok\u00e9mon Red'' and ''Blue'']], and [[Pok\u00e9mon FireRed and LeafGreen|their remakes]], an [[Non-player character|NPC]] will sell the player a Magikarp. A similar character appears in [[Pok\u00e9mon Black and White|''Pok\u00e9mon Black'' and ''White'']]. In [[Pok\u00e9mon Diamond and Pearl|''Pok\u00e9mon Diamond'' and ''Pearl'']], Magikarp appear flopping around in a dried up lake. Outside of the main series, in ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Stadium]]'', Magikarp featured in its own mini game called \"Magikarp Splash\", in which players must Splash high enough to hit the button at the top of the screen as many times as it can. A mobile video game, called ''Pok\u00e9mon: Magikarp Jump'', was announced in February 2017 under the title ''Splash! Magikarp'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Funnell|first1=Rob|title='Splash! Magikarp', a Bizarre New Pokemon Title, Has Been Announced for the App Store|url=http://toucharcade.com/2017/02/16/splash-magikarp-announced/|website=TouchArcade|accessdate=19 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218152008/http://toucharcade.com/2017/02/16/splash-magikarp-announced/|archivedate=18 February 2017}}</ref> and was released for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]] on 25 May 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/a-new-pokemon-game-is-out-now-for-mobile/1100-6450325/|title=A New Pokemon Game Is Out Now For Mobile|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006205545/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/a-new-pokemon-game-is-out-now-for-mobile/1100-6450325/|archivedate=2017-10-06}}</ref>\n\n===In other media===\nIn the anime, Magikarp has appeared several times, most notably as the subject of a running gag in which a salesman attempts to trick [[Team Rocket (anime)|Team Rocket]] into buying Magikarp in various guises, the first one being in ''Battle Aboard the St. Anne''.<ref name=\"Battle Aboard the St. Anne\">{{cite episode| title = Battle Aboard the St. Anne | series = [[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]] | credits = Yukiyoshi \u014chashi (writer) | network = Various | airdate = September 28, 1998 | season = [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Indigo League episodes|Indigo League]]|number = 15}}</ref> In ''The Joy of Pok\u00e9mon'', a [[List of Pok\u00e9mon anime characters#Nurse Joy|Nurse Joy]] from the Orange Islands befriended a giant Magikarp that saved her as a child. It evolved into an equally large Gyarados, but it remained friendly.<ref name=\"The Joy of Pok\u00e9mon\">{{cite episode| title = The Joy of Pok\u00e9mon | series = [[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]] | credits = Junki Takegami (writer) | network = Various | airdate = March 4, 2000 | season = [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Adventures on the Orange Islands episodes|Adventures on the Orange Islands]]|number = 92}}</ref> In ''The Wacky Watcher'', [[Ash Ketchum|Ash]], [[Misty (Pok\u00e9mon)|Misty]] and [[Tracey (Pok\u00e9mon)|Tracey]] help a Pok\u00e9mon Watcher named Dr. Quackenpoker observe the migration and evolution of a school of Magikarp.<ref name=\"The Wacky Watcher!\">{{cite episode| title = The Wacky Watcher! | series = [[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]] | credits = Shinz\u014d Fujita (writer) | network = Various | airdate = September 16, 2000 | season = [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Adventures on the Orange Islands episodes|Adventures on the Orange Islands]]|number = 109}}</ref> Another, in ''Ya See We Want an Evolution'', was nicknamed the strongest Magikarp. This Magikarp was unique in that it was in fact able to battle very well, even knocking out Pikachu.<ref name=\"Ya See We Want an Evolution!\">{{cite episode| title = Ya See We Want an Evolution! | series = [[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]] | credits = Yukiyoshi \u014chashi (writer) | network = Various | airdate = July 10, 2007 | season = [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Diamond and Pearl episodes|Diamond and Pearl]]|number = 21}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:Pokemon Magikarp Taiyaki Pancake from Kurikoan, Akihabara shop, Sotokanda 1-15-1 (\u30b3\u30a4\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\u713c\u304d, \u79cb\u8449\u539f \u304f\u308a\u3053\u5eb5, \u5916\u795e\u75301-15-1) (2017-04-06 13.23.04 by Tokyo Girl).jpg|thumb|A Magikarp shaped [[taiyaki]] served in a restaurant in Japan.]] \n[[GamesRadar]] described it as \"[t]he ultimate in useless Pok\u00e9mon\", though noted its evolution [[Gyarados]] as one of the \"biggest\" characters in the series.<ref name=\"Elston, Brett 9\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/the-complete-pokemon-rby-pokedex-part-12/?page=9 |title=The complete Pokemon RBY Pokedex, part 12 |author=Elston, Brett |page=9 |accessdate=2009-10-03 |publisher=[[Future Publishing]] |work=[[GamesRadar]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306111841/http://www.gamesradar.com/the-complete-pokemon-rby-pokedex-part-12/?page=9 |archivedate=2014-03-06 }}</ref> [[IGN]] called it \"possibly the most docile, unassuming, and weak of all the monsters in the Pok\u00e9mon world\"<ref name=\"Gyarados Biography\">{{cite web |url=http://stars.ign.com/objects/143/14349942_biography.html |title=Gyarados Biography |publisher=[[IGN Entertainment]] |work=[[IGN]] |accessdate=2009-10-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Gt7PCd4D?url=http://stars.ign.com/objects/143/14349942_biography.html |archivedate=2013-05-25 }}</ref> and further described it as serving \"solely as [[comic relief]]\", until its evolution into Gyarados.<ref>{{cite web |author=pokemonofthedaychick |publisher=[[IGN]] |title=Pokemon Crystal Version Pok\u00bfmon of the Day: Magikarp (#129) - IGN FAQs |url=http://faqs.ign.com/articles/374/374951p1.html |date=October 21, 2002 |accessdate=2009-10-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205003104/http://faqs.ign.com/articles/374/374951p1.html |archivedate=February 5, 2009 }}</ref> IGN criticized Magikarp as the \"worst Pok\u00e9mon ever\", citing its low statistics and inability to learn moves from Technical or Hidden Machines, calling it a \"Water wussymon.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guides.ign.com/guides/11154/magikarp.html|title=Video Games, Wikis, Cheats, Walkthroughs, Reviews, News & Videos - IGN|website=IGN|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101023213712/http://guides.ign.com/guides/11154/magikarp.html|archivedate=2010-10-23}}</ref> An IGN guide jokingly noted a trainer in ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Platinum]]'' as having the \"best team among those in the area\" due to having six Magikarps, five of which are unable to attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.guides.ign.com/guides/14254510/page_17.html|title=Pokemon Platinum Guide & Walkthrough - Nintendo DS - IGN|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721092100/http://uk.guides.ign.com/guides/14254510/page_17.html|archivedate=2011-07-21}}</ref> The book ''Gaming Cultures and Place in Asia-Pacific'' cited it as an \"example of a common recurring and weak element\" in the games, whose presence rather than function was to \"emphasize the exclusivity and strength of other, rarer creatures for players to find\".<ref name=\"Surman\">{{cite book |title=Gaming Cultures and Place in Asia-Pacific |last=Hjorth |first=Larissa |author2=David Surman |year=2009 |publisher=Taylor and Francis |isbn=978-0-415-99627-3 |chapter=9 |chapter-url=https://newport.academia.edu/documents/0009/2577/MERGEDPOKEMON.pdf |accessdate=2009-06-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620001743/http://newport.academia.edu/documents/0009/2577/MERGEDPOKEMON.pdf |archivedate=2010-06-20 }}</ref> Loredana Lipperini, author of the book ''Generazione Pok\u00e9mon: i bambini e l'invasione planetaria dei nuovi'', described it as \"innocuous-looking.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MOQc163-XCcC|title=Generazione Pok\u00e9mon: i bambini e l'invasione planetaria dei nuovi \"giocattoli di ruolo\"|first=Loredana|last=Lipperini|date=26 May 2017|publisher=Castelvecchi|via=Google Books|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629011754/http://books.google.com/books?id=MOQc163-XCcC|archivedate=29 June 2011|isbn=9788882102494}}</ref> [[Kotaku]]'s Stephen Totilo also gave criticism to Magikarp, commenting that the using it as his character in ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Rumble]]'' made him learn the \"hard way\" that he \"couldn't have had a worse idea.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5353280/at-last-an-easy-pokemon-game|title=At Last, An Easy Pokemon Game|first=Stephen|last=Totilo|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106201728/http://kotaku.com/5353280/at-last-an-easy-pokemon-game|archivedate=2010-01-06}}</ref> The [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]'s Good Game praised ''[[Pok\u00e9Park Wii: Pikachu's Adventure]]'' for its faithfulness to various Pok\u00e9mon's abilities; while Torterra and Hitmontop were described as using Razor Leaf and Rapid Spin, they merely described Magikarp's actions as just \"being Magikarp.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/abc3/goodgamesp/transcripts/s3033267.htm|title=Good Game Spawn Point - PokePark Wii: Pikachu's Adventure|website=www.abc.net.au|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110922154621/http://www.abc.net.au/abc3/goodgamesp/transcripts/s3033267.htm|archivedate=2011-09-22}}</ref> The web site Bright Side of the Sun used an analogy involving Magikarp, commenting that the words \"defense\" and \"rebounding\" were \"tossed around\" more by their coach to them than \"a Magikarp card at a Pok\u00e9mon convention in 1997.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brightsideofthesun.com/2010/12/5/1856751/phoenix-suns-look-to-continue-defensive-magic-on-john-wall-washington|title=Phoenix Suns Look To Continue Defensive Magic Against John Wall, Washington Wizards|date=5 December 2010|website=Bright Side Of The Sun|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101208062651/http://www.brightsideofthesun.com/2010/12/5/1856751/phoenix-suns-look-to-continue-defensive-magic-on-john-wall-washington|archivedate=8 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal|title=Magikarp: The most useless-seeming monster in the Pokeverse hides an awesome secret|journal=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]|issue=249|date=Jan 2013|pages=122\u2013123}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Video games}}\n* [http://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/Magikarp_(Pok\u00e9mon) Magikarp on Bulbapedia]\n* [https://www.pokeapi.co/api/v2/pokemon/magikarp Magikarp on Pokemon.com]\n\n{{Pok\u00e9mon directory}}\n\n[[Category:Fictional fish]]\n[[Category:Pok\u00e9mon species]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 1996]]\n[[Category:Video game characters with water abilities]]\n\n[[ca:L\u00ednia evolutiva de Magikarp#Magikarp]]\n[[es:Anexo:Pok\u00e9mon de la primera generaci\u00f3n#Magikarp]]\n[[pl:Lista Pok\u00e9mon\u00f3w (121-140)#Magikarp]]\n", "name_user": "Temuera", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magikarp"}
{"title_page": "Tommy Bogan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Tommy Bogan\n| image          =\n| fullname       = Thomas Bogan\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1920|5|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|df=yes|1993|9|23|1920|5|18}}\n| death_place    = [[Alderley Edge]], England\n| height         = \n| position       = [[Midfielder#Winger|Outside right]]\n| youthyears1    = |youthclubs1 = [[Strathclyde F.C.|Strathclyde]]\n| youthyears2    = |youthclubs2 = [[Blantyre Celtic F.C.|Blantyre Celtic]]\n| youthyears3    = |youthclubs3 = [[Renfrew F.C.|Renfrew]]\n| years1         = 1943\u20131946 |clubs1 = [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]]                 |caps1 = 0 |goals1 = 0\n| years2         = 1946\u20131948 |clubs2 = [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]                       |caps2 = 34 |goals2 = 5\n| years3         = 1948\u20131949 |clubs3 = [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] |caps3 = 11 |goals3 = 0\n| years4         = 1949\u20131951 |clubs4 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] |caps4 = 29 |goals4 = 7\n| years5         = 1951      |clubs5 = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]                   |caps5 = 4 |goals5 = 1\n| years6         = 1951\u20131953 |clubs6 = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]             |caps6 = 8 |goals6 = 2\n| years7         = 1953\u20131954 |clubs7 = [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]   |caps7 = 1 |goals7 = 0\n| years8         = 1954\u20131955 |clubs8 = [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]] |caps8 = 27 |goals8 = 14\n| nationalyears1 = 1948\n| nationalteam1  = [[Scottish League XI]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/players/tommybogan.html|title=Tommy Bogan|work=Londonhearts.com|publisher=London Hearts Supporters' Club|accessdate=18 December 2011}}</ref>\n| nationalcaps1  = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1945\n| nationalteam2 = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] (wartime)\n| nationalcaps2 = 1\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n}}\n'''Thomas Bogan''' (18 May 1920 \u2013 23 September 1993) was a Scottish [[association football|footballer]],<ref>{{Hugman|1810|accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref> who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for several clubs in both Scotland and England. Born in [[Glasgow]], Bogan played for [[Strathclyde F.C.|Strathclyde]], [[Blantyre Celtic F.C.|Blantyre Celtic]], [[Renfrew F.C.|Renfrew]] and [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] before moving to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] after the end of the [[World War II|Second World War]].\n\nAfter two-and-a-half years with Celtic, Bogan moved to England to play for [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] in September 1948. He played for Preston for one season, before moving to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in September 1949. However, it was apparent that Bogan had not adapted to the English game and moved back to Scotland to play for [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] in March 1951. A move back to England soon followed, with Bogan moving to [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] after just four appearances for Aberdeen. Again, though, he struggled to fit in and he moved to [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] and then [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]] before retiring from professional football.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Sources\n*[http://www.londonhearts.com/scotlandunoff/players/tommybogan.html London Hearts profile]\n*[http://www.stretfordend.co.uk/playermenu/bogan.html Profile] at StretfordEnd.co.uk\n*[http://www.mufcinfo.com/manupag/a-z_player_archive/a-z_player_archive_pages/bogan_thomas.html Profile] at MUFCInfo.com\n*{{NeilBrownPlayers|player1/tommybogan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bogan, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Hibernian F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Celtic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Preston North End F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aberdeen F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southampton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Blackburn Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Macclesfield Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:Renfrew F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scotland wartime international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Junior Football Association players]]\n[[Category:Blantyre Celtic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Strathclyde F.C. players]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-footy-forward-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Tommy Bogan\n| image          =\n| fullname       = Thomas Bogan\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1920|5|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|df=yes|1993|9|23|1920|5|18}}\n| death_place    = [[Alderley Edge]], England\n| height         = \n| position       = [[Midfielder#Winger|Outside right]]\n| youthyears1    = |youthclubs1 = [[Strathclyde F.C.|Strathclyde]]\n| youthyears2    = |youthclubs2 = [[Blantyre Celtic F.C.|Blantyre Celtic]]\n| youthyears3    = |youthclubs3 = [[Renfrew F.C.|Renfrew]]\n| years1         = 1943\u20131946 |clubs1 = [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]]                 |caps1 = 0 |goals1 = 0\n| years2         = 1946\u20131948 |clubs2 = [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]                       |caps2 = 34 |goals2 = 5\n| years3         = 1948\u20131949 |clubs3 = [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] |caps3 = 11 |goals3 = 0\n| years4         = 1949\u20131951 |clubs4 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] |caps4 = 29 |goals4 = 7\n| years5         = 1951      |clubs5 = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]                   |caps5 = 4 |goals5 = 1\n| years6         = 1951\u20131953 |clubs6 = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]             |caps6 = 8 |goals6 = 2\n| years7         = 1953\u20131954 |clubs7 = [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]   |caps7 = 1 |goals7 = 0\n| years8         = 1954\u20131955 |clubs8 = [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]] |caps8 = 27 |goals8 = 14\n| nationalyears1 = 1948\n| nationalteam1  = [[Scottish League XI]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/players/tommybogan.html|title=Tommy Bogan|work=Londonhearts.com|publisher=London Hearts Supporters' Club|accessdate=18 December 2011}}</ref>\n| nationalcaps1  = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1945\n| nationalteam2 = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] (wartime)\n| nationalcaps2 = 1\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n}}\n'''Thomas Bogan''' (18 May 1920 \u2013 23 September 1993) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[association football|footballer]],<ref>{{Hugman|1810|accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref> who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for several clubs in both Scotland and England. Born in [[Glasgow]], Bogan played for [[Strathclyde F.C.|Strathclyde]], [[Blantyre Celtic F.C.|Blantyre Celtic]], [[Renfrew F.C.|Renfrew]] and [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] before moving to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] after the end of the [[World War II|Second World War]].\n\nAfter two-and-a-half years with Celtic, Bogan moved to England to play for [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] in September 1948. He played for Preston for one season, before moving to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in September 1949. However, it was apparent that Bogan had not adapted to the English game and moved back to Scotland to play for [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] in March 1951. A move back to England soon followed, with Bogan moving to [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] after just four appearances for Aberdeen. Again, though, he struggled to fit in and he moved to [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] and then [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]] before retiring from professional football.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\